A Call for Data on the Principal Pipeline
Frank Perrone, Michelle D. Young, & Edward J. Fuller
[FINAL VERSION ACCEPTED FOR PUBLICATION]
This is an accepted manuscript of an article published by Sage Publishing in Educational
Researcher on February 3, 2022, available at: https://doi.org/10.3102/0013189X221075767
Final Article Citation:
Perrone, F., Young, M. D., & Fuller, E. J. (2022). A call for data on the principal pipeline.
Educational Researcher, 51(6), 423-430. https://doi.org/10.3102/0013189X221075767
Abstract
In this policy forum commentary, we call for improved national and state-level data collection
and access relevant to the principal pipeline. We focus specifically on how access to quality data
can inform, has informed, and is critical to policy and practice across three segments of the
principal pipeline—principal preparation, licensure, and labor markets—as well as the essential
issue of diversity itself and across each pipeline segment. We also outline and explain the types
of data collection, storage, and access that would enable more informed and relevant principal
pipeline research, policy, and preparation. We then call for action at the state and the federal
levels, including reauthorization of the Higher Education Act to expand Title II educator data
collection to include principal preparation programs as it does teacher preparation programs.
Finally, we conclude with cautions against potential data misuse.
Keywords: educational policy; principals; leadership; research methodology

graduates employed in leadership positions. Thus, Tier 3 data are more difficult to collect and

Many, if not all, of Tier 1 and Tier 2 data are currently collected by states and/or the
USDoE. Specifically, similar teacher data are already collected by states, and similar teacher
preparation program data are already collected by both states and the USDoE. Thus, the Tier 1
and Tier 2 data about principals and PPPs should be relatively easy to collect and make
available. Tier 1 licensure data are already collected by states, and Tier 2 data could be collected
by states on their own licensure tests or in collaboration with testing companies. Tier 3 data are
more difficult and costly to collect, organize, and store, thus they may require additional effort
and fiscal support. We propose a potential solution to this issue later in the paper.
Informing Policy and Practice with Principal Pipeline Data
We contend states and the U.S. Department of Education, in partnership with
organizations such as the National Policy Board for Educational Administration (an alliance of
the AASA, CCSSO, ICPEL, NASSP, NAESP, and UCEA), National Governors Association,
National Council of State Legislators, and funders of educational research intended to inform
practice and policy, need to collect and make available principal pipeline data to better focus
resources where they are most needed to ensure every student has access to effective school
leaders. In this essay, we focus on three sections of the principal pipeline—PPP quality, principal
licensure, principal labor market—and equity and representation across all areas. Each of these is
described below.
Preparation Quality
Data to be Collected on Preparation Quality
Available evidence suggests PPPs influence leader abilities to improve various teacher
and student outcomes (e.g., Darling-Hammond et al., 2007; Orphanos & Orr, 2014) and that
there are variations in PPP quality (e.g., Fuller & Hollingworth, 2018; Grissom, Mitani, & Woo,
2019). Greater availability of data would certainly increase our knowledge of effective PPP
practices. States, then, should invest in collecting and managing an array of data that can help
improve the quality of PPPs and the ability of their graduates to improve student outcomes and
address issues of equity. Basic measures of quality would include Tier 1 data on the number of
graduates, graduates obtaining employment, and graduates remaining in leadership positions.
More advanced measures of quality would require Tier 2 and 3 data on PPP course content,
clinical experiences, aggregate and individual licensure test data, individual employment
pathways, and estimates of principal effectiveness relative to student outcomes. In addition,
surveys of current and former students, such as the INSPIRE surveys that programs across
multiple states continue to use, would provide direct measures of quality from the viewpoint of
the educators receiving the preparation and can be merged with other state data. The collection of
Tier 3 data across the preparation, licensure, and employment areas would allow researchers to
examine more distal measures of PPP quality, such as the impact of graduates on teacher and
student outcomes (e.g., Fuller & Hollingworth, 2018; Grissom, Mitani, & Woo, 2019), the
outcomes (e.g, test scores, discipline rates, graduation rates, attendance rates).

In general, this body of research using state administrative datasets (mostly data from
Missouri, New York, Illinois, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas) has concluded that more
individuals obtain licensure than the number of vacancies each year, between 50% and 75% of
those obtaining principal licensure become employed as a principal or in a school leadership
position, the average years from licensure to employment as a principal is about five years
(Bastian & Henry, 2015; Davis et al., 2017), an increasing number of newly licensed principals
become an assistant principal prior to becoming a principal (Crawford & Fuller, 2016; Fuller et
al., 2019), principal attrition and turnover are higher than teacher attrition and turnover (e.g.,
Bartanen, & Mitani, 2019), and salaries incentivize principals to move from one school to
another (e.g., Baker et al., 2010; Pendola, 2021). To what extent these findings hold across
individual labor markets and states is only speculation, given the lack of available data to
conduct similar studies elsewhere. The National Teacher and Principal Survey (NTPS)
administered by the National Center for Education Statistics (https://nces.ed.gov/surveys/ntps/)
does provide important nationally representative information about turnover and the factors
associated with turnover, such as working conditions (e.g., Snodgrass Rangel, 2018;
Tekleselassie & Choi, 2019). The NTPS data, however, does not provide information at either
the state or labor market level nor any information regarding PPP enrollments or the supply of
licensed school leaders. Additionally, the Common Core of Data (https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/) does
not differentiate administrator counts by role (e.g., principal, assistant principal), meaning that
pools of potential principals working in the assistant principal rank, for instance, cannot be
calculated.
Moreover, they should establish a tapping procedure that explicitly identifies teachers of color
and female teachers for entry into a PPP. Further, district policymakers should use disaggregated
state PPP data to identify PPPs graduating leaders of color and establish district-university
partnerships with those PPPs.
PPP leaders should examine the personal characteristics of those recruited and selected
into their program as well as their graduates as the first step in examining the degree to which
their recruitment, selection, and support processes lead to the graduation and placement of
leaders of color and female leaders. Further, PPPs should examine the effectiveness of their
graduates in serving the needs of students living in poverty and students of color. Finally, PPPs
should develop district-university partnerships to enhance their recruitment and placement of
educators of color and female educators.
State policymakers should collect data on the individual demographic characteristics of
PPP enrollees, graduates, licensure test-takers, individuals obtaining licensure, employed school
leaders, and leaders leaving the profession. In doing so, the strengths and weaknesses of the
pipeline can be identified. The collection of Tier 2 and 3 data, especially surveys of individuals,
would help determine the specific factors associated with preparing, employing, and retaining a
greater number and percentage of leaders of color and female leaders. These lessons learned
could then be used to assist PPPs in improving their practice and help school districts create
more effective and equitable hiring and retention strategies. Indeed, collecting and making
available Tier 2 and 3 data on principals (and teachers) is vital to ensuring that every student—
regardless of race/ethnicity—has an equal opportunity to learn and maximize their potential.
Policy Avenues to Increase Data Collection and Access
In stark contrast to PPP data, national and state-level teacher preparation program (TPP)
data have been collected and made publicly available through Title II: Teacher Quality
Enhancement of the Higher Education Act (HEA). Similar collection and release of relevant PPP
data would provide researchers and policymakers critical information for the benefit of K-12
education. Currently, Title II requires all U.S. states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and
outlying territories to annually report various TPP information to the USDoE since 2010 (U.S.
Department of Education, 2016). States are required to report an array of information, including:
number of TPPs and subject area programs, TPP type (traditional or alternative), aggregate grade
point averages of students, requirements for initial licensure, state policies governing
certification, student enrollment, number of completers, licensure pass rates by test, and
identification of at-risk programs. The data is disaggregated by state, TPP, and program
(generally teacher subject area). The enrollment data is also disaggregated by race/ethnicity and
gender. All the data are publicly available (https://title2.ed.gov/Public/DataTools/Tables.aspx)
and provide valuable information for education research and to inform policy concerning teacher
preparation, certification, and licensure. Used in conjunction with national teacher turnover data,
Title II data has informed policy around national (e.g., Sutcher et al., 2016) and state (e.g., Wan
et al., 2019) teacher supply and demand. Title II-based reports cannot fully address locality and
hard-to-staff schools in the supply/demand equation (e.g., Cowan et al., 2016), but do offer
policymakers valuable proxies of national and state-level teacher supply whereas for principals
there is none.
Identical data collection for PPPs and licensure may provide more accurate pictures of
the public school principal labor market than the teacher labor market due to its relative size (3.7
million public school teachers, less than 100,000 principal principals; USDoE, 2018) and being
